Benchmark Datasets and Evaluation Methodologies for Automated Code Smell DetectionThe Architecture of Technical Debt and the Necessity of Ground TruthThe detection, classification, and remediation of code smells represent a critical frontier in software maintenance, continuous integration, and the proactive management of technical debt. Code smells, originally conceptualized as surface indications that usually correspond to a deeper structural or architectural problem in a software system, serve as heuristic markers for poor object-oriented design and suboptimal implementation choices. Unlike functional bugs or explicit syntax errors, which manifest as immediate execution failures, compilation halts, or incorrect outputs, code smells are insidious architectural and stylistic anti-patterns. Phenomena such as bloated classes, overly complex methods, or excessive evolutionary coupling degrade code comprehensibility, hinder evolutionary maintenance, and exponentially elevate long-term fault-proneness.Historically, automated code smell identification relied predominantly on structural static analysis techniques grounded in heuristics, coupling-cohesion metrics, and distance-based similarity measures. Early analytical tools applied rigid, manually crafted rules and numerical thresholds to detect anomalies within source code syntax trees. However, the inherent subjectivity of software design architecture dictates a fundamental challenge: what constitutes a deleterious "smell" to one developer may represent a perfectly justifiable, domain-specific architectural compromise to another. This persistent subjectivity has historically plagued the evaluation of automated detection tools, resulting in exceptionally high false-positive rates and significant disagreement among competitive approaches analyzing the exact same codebases.To mature the field from heuristic-based guessing to rigorous, empirically validated detection—particularly with the advent of machine learning architectures and large language model (LLM) based program analysis—the software engineering research community required standardized, reproducible ground-truth oracles. The formulation, validation, and adoption of these benchmark datasets have become the absolute cornerstone of methodological evaluation. Evaluating an automated detector's precision, recall, and F-measure is mathematically impossible without a mutually agreed-upon baseline defining what constitutes a true positive code smell.This exhaustive analysis provides a comprehensive examination of the benchmark datasets and evaluation methodologies deployed for automated code smell detectors. It systematically explores general software quality benchmarks, specifically Defects4J and ManySStuBs4J, before detailing the most critical ground-truth oracles engineered specifically for code smells: the Palomba et al. Landfill dataset, the Fontana et al. machine learning dataset, and the industry-calibrated MLCQ dataset. Furthermore, the analysis scrutinizes the evaluative performance—measured in empirical precision and recall—of state-of-the-art detection tools, explores the emerging necessity of cross-language transfer learning, and critically assesses the theoretical boundaries placed on algorithmic precision by human inter-rater reliability ceilings.Foundational Benchmarks: Program Repair and Single-Statement AnomaliesBefore examining domain-specific code smell oracles, it is methodologically essential to contextualize the broader landscape of software quality benchmarks. Two extensive datasets, Defects4J and ManySStuBs4J, are ubiquitous in modern software engineering research. While their primary operational parameters are utilized for automated program repair (APR) and fault localization, they intersect meaningfully and frequently with code smell research, as architectural anti-patterns are frequently the underlying structural catalysts for the specific functional bugs cataloged in these repositories.Defects4J: Tangled Refactoring and Reproducible FaultsDefects4J is a curated, highly structured database of real-world, reproducible bugs extracted systematically from active open-source Java projects. Designed specifically to enable controlled testing studies and rigorously evaluate automated program repair algorithms, Defects4J provides an isolated programmatic environment where the buggy source code, the developer-written patch, and the triggering test suite are packaged together.While Defects4J is heavily leveraged for behavioral bug resolution, its relevance to code smell detection is deeply nuanced and increasingly critical. Longitudinal studies tracking the lifecycle of bugs within the Defects4J dataset reveal that many functional faults are deeply intertwined with underlying code smells. For instance, complex multi-chunk bugs often reside within God Classes or Long Methods, where bloated scopes, shadowed variables, and entangled logic obscure execution paths, directly causing the fault.Furthermore, the act of repairing a bug in Defects4J is rarely a surgically sterile operation; it is often conflated with code smell remediation. Several of the developer-submitted patches in Defects4J inadvertently combine the functional repair with structural refactoring. This tangling of bug-fixing and bug-inducing changes within the same commit significantly complicates evaluation methodologies. Neglecting to account for refactoring within the dataset introduces severe bias into the learning and evaluation of prediction models. Research into Just-In-Time Defect Prediction (JIT-DP) demonstrates that failing to consider refactoring information in datasets like JIT-Defects4J can diminish the performance of semantic-based prediction models by 18.6% and up to 37.3% in F1-score. Conversely, incorporating code change tactics (CAT) analysis to categorize refactoring and its propagation improves dataset labeling accuracy by 13.7%, resulting in overall improvements in automated recall by up to 43.2%.Recent evaluations of state-of-the-art models on Defects4J highlight the dual nature of code generation and architectural degradation. A 2025 study utilizing GPT-4 on the Defects4J dataset achieved an impressive bug-detection accuracy of 89.7% and a mitigation efficacy of 86.4%. However, when automated program repair tools (such as Sorald) are evaluated against complex benchmarks, studies show that while they may successfully fix a specific rule violation, they frequently introduce massive numbers of new architectural violations—in one study, introducing 2,120 new faults, including 2,088 newly generated code smells, thereby reducing the long-term maintainability of the code. Thus, while Defects4J is excellent for evaluating functional correctness, its patches sometimes combine bug fixes with purely stylistic refactoring, meaning it cannot serve as an isolated oracle for pure code smell precision and recall.ManySStuBs4J: Structural Anti-Patterns and LLM EvaluationsThe ManySStuBs4J dataset provides a massive, highly granular repository comprising over 150,000 single-statement Java bugs, categorized meticulously into 16 distinct bug patterns, mined directly from developer commit histories. Unlike the complex, multi-file architectural faults in Defects4J, the instances cataloged in ManySStuBs4J are characterized by highly localized diffs—often spanning a total contextual length of only 13 lines of code.The methodology behind ManySStuBs4J relies on sophisticated static analysis to compare the Abstract Syntax Trees (ASTs) of candidate buggy and fixed programs, systematically searching for specific bug-fix patterns. Several of these granular patterns border on microscopic code smells. For example, the dataset catalogs the misuse of Boolean flags in method signatures—a well-known code smell that severely reduces code readability and API usability by obfuscating developer intent. Similarly, the SWAP_ARGUMENTS pattern, where developers invoke a correct method but transpose the parameter order, is highly indicative of the Long Parameter List smell or poorly encapsulated data structures, a common anti-pattern in Java since the language historically lacks named parameters.ManySStuBs4J has become highly relevant for evaluating the code generation and repair capabilities of modern LLMs, such as CodeBERT, Codex, and GPT architectures. Evaluation methodologies utilizing ManySStuBs4J demonstrate that finely tuned models like CodeBERT can achieve accuracies ranging from 68.8% to 72% in predicting developer-implemented fixes in less than a second per bug.However, LLM evaluations on ManySStuBs4J also reveal significant challenges regarding the generation of code smells. Studies testing Codex on the dataset found that while the model could avoid 13.41% of known simple bugs (SStuBs), it frequently recapitulated bugs and structural smells seen in its training data. Furthermore, evaluations of smaller open-source LLMs against benchmarks like ManySStuBs4J and MBPP reveal that there is roughly a 19.1% chance of an LLM-generated solution containing a distinct code smell, emphasizing that models remain highly prone to propagating buggy, smelly variants when they are the dominant patterns observed in uncurated repositories.Feature / CharacteristicDefects4J BenchmarkManySStuBs4J BenchmarkPrimary Use CaseAutomated Program Repair, Fault LocalizationSingle-statement bug analysis, LLM repair evaluationScale and VolumeHundreds of complex, multi-chunk bugsOver 150,000 localized, single-statement bugsCode Scope per InstanceBroad; often spans multiple classes and methodsHighly localized; average 13 lines of code including contextRelation to Code SmellsBug patches often conflated with structural refactoringCaptures microscopic smells (e.g., Boolean flags, swapped args)LLM Evaluative Findings89.7% detection accuracy (GPT-4); patches can induce new smells19-72% repair accuracy (CodeBERT); models often recapitulate smellsGround-Truth Oracles for Code Smell DetectionThe rigorous evaluation of code smell detection algorithms requires datasets explicitly annotated for architectural anomalies rather than behavioral execution failures. The historical absence of comprehensive, manually annotated sets of such smells forced researchers to build ad-hoc, localized oracles, which severely limited the external validity and comparability of different detection techniques. Over the past decade, the community has converged upon three pivotal datasets that serve to standardize this evaluation: the Palomba et al. Landfill dataset, the Arcelli Fontana et al. machine learning dataset, and the industry-relevant MLCQ dataset.The Palomba et al. Landfill DatasetThe Landfill dataset, curated and published by Palomba et al., represents one of the earliest and most rigorously manually validated ground-truth oracles for code smell evaluation. Constructed specifically to mitigate oracle subjectiveness and provide a standardized baseline for comparing detection accuracy, Landfill contains 243 meticulously validated instances of five distinct types of code smells across 20 open-source software projects.The five code smells targeted by the Landfill dataset encompass both structural bloat and complex evolutionary coupling :Blob (God Class): Large, highly complex classes that centralize the system's behavior, implement multiple disparate responsibilities, possess a high number of attributes or operations, and depend extensively on simple data holding classes.Feature Envy: Methods that are excessively interested in the data of other classes, frequently invoking the accessor methods of another class to utilize its data rather than operating on their own internal state.Divergent Change: An evolutionary smell occurring when a single class must be modified in different ways for different reasons over time (e.g., modifying three methods for a new database connection and four different methods for a new financial instrument).Shotgun Surgery: The inverse of Divergent Change; occurs when a single conceptual change triggers numerous, minute modifications across several disparate classes.Parallel Inheritance: An architectural flaw where making a subclass of one class requires the simultaneous creation of a corresponding subclass in another hierarchy.The 20 object systems evaluated in the Landfill dataset include heavily utilized open-source systems of varying scales. Notable inclusions are Apache Ant (846 classes, 173 KLOC), Apache Tomcat (1,284 classes, 336 KLOC), jEdit (316 classes, 101 KLOC), Android API frameworks, Eclipse Core (1,190 classes, 162 KLOC), and Apache Cassandra. To effectively accommodate history-based detection tools that require longitudinal data, the dataset methodology involved splitting the history of each project in half and constructing the oracle using a specific Git snapshot extracted from the exact chronological midpoint.The manual validation methodology deployed for Landfill was highly structured to minimize error and human subjectiveness. First, a primary annotator spent approximately four weeks manually inspecting the source code and historical change data of the midpoint snapshots, guided by formal literature definitions of the smells. Subsequently, a secondary annotator performed an independent cross-validation to ensure correctness. This cross-validation flagged only six disputed instances. Through open discussion, two instances were confirmed as false positives and purged from the dataset, while four were retained. While a 243-instance dataset cannot claim exhaustive, total coverage of every unrecorded smell within the 20 systems, this rigorous dual-annotator verification ensures an exceptionally high-confidence baseline, ensuring that any tool evaluated against Landfill is benchmarking against undeniable architectural violations.The Fontana et al. Machine Learning DatasetWhile the Landfill dataset prioritized deep manual validation on a deliberately small scale, Arcelli Fontana et al. engineered a dataset explicitly designed to facilitate the training and empirical evaluation of machine learning models for code smell detection. This dataset fundamentally shifted the paradigm from heuristic rule creation to algorithmic pattern recognition, formally treating smell detection as a multi-label classification problem.The Fontana dataset comprises candidate instances extracted from 74 heterogeneous open-source Java systems sourced from the Tempero et al. Qualitas Corpus. It focuses its analytical lens on four highly prevalent structural smells :Data Class: Classes operating merely as data containers with exposed attributes and minimal complex functionality, severely impacting data abstraction and encapsulation dimensions.God Class (Brain Class): Highly complex classes centralizing system intelligence, characterized by high coupling, low cohesion, and excessive size.Feature Envy: Methods overly reliant on external class data, utilizing more attributes from foreign providers than from their own host class.Long Method (God Method): Extremely lengthy, highly complex, and uncohesive methods that centralize class functionality and resist comprehension.To construct the baseline dataset, Fontana et al. computed a massive, comprehensive matrix of object-oriented metrics for all 74 systems, which serve as the independent feature variables for the learning algorithms. Up to 82 distinct metrics were preserved, including critical indicators such as the Number of Accessor Methods (NOAM), Weighted Method Count (WMCNAMM), Access to Foreign Data (ATFD), Locality of Attribute Accesses (LAA), and Response for a Class (RFC).To establish the ground truth efficiently, the researchers utilized a stratified random sampling approach. They executed multiple pre-existing heuristic detection tools (referred to as "Advisors") over the extensive codebase to locate candidate instances. A total of 1,986 candidate instances were subsequently manually evaluated. This manual labeling phase revealed a crucial, paradigm-shifting insight into the state of traditional heuristic detectors: of the 1,986 candidates confidently flagged by various heuristic Advisors, only 826 were confirmed by humans as true positive smells, while 1,160 were rejected as false positives. This massive false-positive rate definitively underscored the necessity of machine learning algorithms capable of parsing complex, non-linear metric relationships rather than relying on strict, brittle numerical thresholds.Ultimately, the study isolated a perfectly balanced training dataset of 420 instances (140 positive, 280 negative) for each of the four smells. When evaluated via algorithmic cross-validation utilizing 16 machine learning algorithms (expanded to 32 with boosting configurations), the dataset demonstrated that robust algorithms like J48 and Random Forest could achieve greater than 96% accuracy. Conversely, models lacking robust feature selection steps, such as basic Support Vector Machines (SVM), achieved the worst performance metrics. Later iterations of this foundational work by independent researchers expanded the dataset significantly, such as the SmellyCode++ dataset, which merged these metrics into a massive 107,000-instance multi-label structure to support deep learning applications.MLCQ: Industry-Relevant Subjectivity and SeverityWhile the Landfill and Fontana datasets vastly advanced the empirical foundation of the field, they relied heavily on legacy academic criteria and utilized graduate students as primary evaluators. The MLCQ (Madeyski Lewowski Code Quest) dataset was specifically engineered to transcend these academic limitations by capturing the contemporary, practical intuition of professional software engineers operating in active industrial environments.MLCQ provides an immense corpus of 14,739 individual reviews covering 4,770 distinct code samples extracted from contemporary, industry-relevant Java open-source projects hosted on GitHub. It focuses on the same four ubiquitous object-oriented smells as the Fontana dataset: Blob, Data Class, Feature Envy, and Long Method.The dataset's most significant methodological advancement lies in its reviewer demographic pool. Rather than relying on students, MLCQ utilized 26 professional developers: 8 senior/lead developers, 4 regular developers, 8 junior developers (recruited from MSc tracks but strictly possessing verified industrial experience), and 6 developers of undisclosed backgrounds. To provide deep contextual mapping, 20 of these developers completed an exhaustive 59-question survey detailing their professional experience, known paradigms, and review habits. These professionals evaluated the code samples and assigned a critical severity rating on a four-level ordinal scale: critical, major, minor, and none.To guarantee high reliability, the MLCQ dataset incorporates rigorous conflict resolution and cross-validation. Any code sample that received only a single review, or received two reviews with conflicting severity ratings, was forcefully routed into a cross-check phase for mandatory re-evaluation by entirely different developers.Crucially, in a deliberate departure from the Fontana methodology, the MLCQ dataset explicitly does not include pre-calculated source code metrics. Each dataset record provides the exact GitHub link, precise review timestamp, and a fully qualified code name. By decoupling the human evaluations from a fixed set of static metrics (like WMC or ATFD), the dataset prevents researchers from overfitting their algorithms to specific object-oriented formulas. Instead, it forces model architects to extract their own representations—such as Abstract Syntax Trees, token streams, or LLM embeddings—directly from the raw, contemporary source code. Recent studies utilizing the MLCQ dataset to evaluate the general-purpose LLM GPT-4o mini via zero-shot, few-shot, and chain-of-thought prompting strategies revealed that while chain-of-thought prompting yielded the most balanced performance across Blob and Data Class smells, the model persistently struggled with Feature Envy detection regardless of the prompting strategy applied.Comparative Evaluation of State-of-the-Art Detection ToolsWith robust ground-truth datasets formally established, researchers have extensively benchmarked the precision, recall, and F-measure of automated detection tools. A fundamental methodological split exists within the tooling landscape between traditional static analysis tools—which evaluate structural metrics from a single, frozen snapshot of code—and evolutionary tools that analyze the chronological change history of a repository.Structural Static Analysis: JDeodorant, PMD, Checkstyle, SonarQube, and iPlasmaThe vast majority of early automated code smell detection relied entirely on structural static analysis. Tools like JDeodorant, PMD, Checkstyle, SonarQube, and iPlasma process source code to construct an AST or compute object-oriented metrics, and subsequently apply heuristic rules to identify anomalies.JDeodorant: Functioning as an Eclipse plug-in, JDeodorant is highly utilized in academic validation and focuses heavily on detecting God Class, Feature Envy, Long Method, and Type Checking anomalies. It employs sophisticated metric thresholds and precondition-oriented methods to not only detect smells but to algorithmically propose behavior-preserving refactorings directly to the developer.iPlasma: An integrated analysis environment that pioneered the use of "detection strategies"—mechanisms that capture deviations from good design principles by defining a hierarchical list of rules based on interacting metrics and their respective thresholds. iPlasma is frequently deployed alongside JDeodorant to provide comparative baselining in rigorous empirical studies.PMD and Checkstyle: Widely adopted in enterprise industry pipelines, these tools operate as highly configurable static analyzers. However, their empirical performance in rigorous architectural smell detection is highly mixed. In comprehensive comparative studies, Checkstyle has occasionally been discarded entirely from evaluation for failing to detect any instances of complex architectural smells, as its default ruleset is heavily skewed toward stylistic syntax enforcement rather than deep structural anomaly detection. PMD performs markedly better but relies heavily on user-configured, static thresholds that fail to adapt to varied domain architectures.SonarQube: Operating as a modern continuous inspection platform, SonarQube evaluates code against dynamic maintainability rules. Studies evaluating LLM-generated code frequently rely on SonarQube as an automated baseline oracle. For instance, empirical evaluations reveal that when an LLM generates flawed code, SonarQube successfully identifies maintainability issues (explicitly classified as code smells) in roughly 88% of those cases, highlighting its robustness as a baseline syntactic filter.Heuristic Discrepancies and Evaluative OverlapA persistent, fundamental challenge highlighted by rigorous evaluation methodologies is the profound lack of agreement between these traditional static tools. When tools like PMD and JDeodorant are simultaneously applied to the exact same codebase to detect a God Class, they detect the smell only partially and with significant differences in scope, primarily because they prioritize entirely different underlying metrics in their proprietary detection strategies.Consequently, tools evaluated against the same ground-truth dataset will yield wildly divergent precision and recall metrics. Traditional heuristics often achieve artificially high recall at the devastating expense of precision, effectively flooding developers with false positives and rendering the tool practically useless in high-velocity production environments.Evolutionary Detection: The HIST Tool MethodologyRecognizing that purely structural snapshot analysis fundamentally misses the temporal nature of accumulating technical debt, Palomba et al. developed HIST (Historical Information for Smell deTection). The central theoretical thesis of HIST posits that certain complex smells—specifically Divergent Change, Shotgun Surgery, and Parallel Inheritance—are intrinsically evolutionary and mathematically invisible to a single snapshot. Instead, they are characterized entirely by how code elements change synchronously or asynchronously over time across multiple commits.HIST operationalizes this theory by algorithmically analyzing Git commit histories, extracting fine-grained changes, and mining association rules between code elements. In a highly rigorous comparative study involving 20 open-source projects, HIST was evaluated directly against state-of-the-art structural smell detectors. The evaluation demonstrated that HIST achieved a precision ranging tightly between 72% and 86%, and an impressive recall ranging between 58% and 100%, depending on the specific smell and software architecture.More significantly, the empirical results proved that HIST was capable of successfully identifying deeply embedded code smells that could not be identified through approaches relying solely on static structural code analysis. To validate the practical relevance of these automated findings, a secondary qualitative study involving 12 original developers from the analyzed projects confirmed that over 75% of the specific smell instances detected by HIST were genuinely perceived by the human architects as actual, pressing design flaws requiring immediate refactoring intervention.Cross-Language Generalization in Code Smell DetectionA pervasive, deeply entrenched limitation in historical code smell research is an overwhelming, systemic bias toward the Java programming language. The seminal ground-truth datasets anchoring the field—Landfill, Fontana, and MLCQ—are exclusively composed of open-source Java projects. Consequently, the heuristic rulesets, precise metric thresholds, and machine learning models trained on these datasets are tightly coupled to the structural, semantic, and syntactic paradigms of Java. This raises a critical methodological vulnerability: do automated detectors trained or tuned exclusively on Java generalize reliably to other object-oriented paradigms?The Multi-Lingual Evaluation Gap and Benchmark LimitationsObject-oriented design philosophies manifest radically differently across static and dynamic typing paradigms. The structural variations observed in Lines of Code (LOC), method counts, attribute visibility, and class inheritance across languages like C# and Python dictate that a specific numerical threshold for a God Class optimized for Java may trigger a cascade of false positives when applied to Python. Existing studies reliant on individual classifiers and unbalanced, Java-centric datasets generally fail to account for how these programming language paradigms fundamentally influence the design and effectiveness of ML-based detection approaches.Recent broad-scale initiatives have begun addressing this evaluative gap by testing the cross-language generalizability of LLMs and machine learning ensembles. Multi-lingual datasets such as BeetleBox provide comprehensive fault matrices across five diverse programming languages (Java, C++, Python, Go, and JavaScript) encompassing 23,782 bugs, though they are primarily targeted at bug localization rather than purely architectural code smells. Similarly, the CRUXEVAL-X benchmark establishes a multi-lingual code reasoning dataset covering 19 programming languages. Intensive evaluation of 24 representative LLMs against CRUXEVAL-X reveals stark limitations: a model trained solely on Python achieves at most a 34.4% Pass@1 rate in other languages, empirically demonstrating the severe performance degradation models suffer when forced across language barriers.Transfer Learning for Code Smell GeneralizationTo bypass the prohibitively expensive and labor-intensive process of manually curating, annotating, and cross-checking distinct code smell oracles for every individual programming language, researchers are actively evaluating Transfer Learning (TL) methodologies. The core scientific objective is to determine if deep learning models and ensemble classifiers can successfully learn foundational architectural features in a highly annotated, data-rich source language (Java) and reliably detect analogous smells in a sparsely annotated target language (C# or Python) without requiring extensive, language-specific feature engineering.Empirical evaluations of this cross-lingual approach yield highly promising results. In a robust study applying deep learning models—specifically Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs), and autoencoders—trained on C# and evaluated directly over Java code samples (and vice-versa), researchers concluded that transfer learning for implementation smells achieved performance metrics highly comparable to direct, in-domain direct-learning methods.Further rigorous research explicitly evaluated instance-based transfer learning methodologies (utilizing techniques like Importance Weighting Classifiers and Transfer AdaBoost) against parameter-based approaches (Transfer Tree, Transfer Forest). Utilizing Java as the data-rich source dataset and mapping to C# and Python as the target datasets, the study focused on detecting Large Class, Long Method, and Long Parameter List smells. The empirical results demonstrated that the instance-based approach definitively outperformed parameter-based methods. Specifically, Transfer AdaBoost, when coupled with Gradient Boosting and Extra Trees ensemble learning base models, achieved exceptionally consistent and robust detection results across both target languages, boasting an 83% statistical winning rate as validated by the Wilcoxon signed-rank test.Furthermore, the deployment of dynamic stacking ensembles combining multiple baseline classifiers has been empirically validated using diverse, multi-lingual Java and Python datasets. These studies prove that computationally simpler ensemble structures can successfully maintain stable, superior code smell detection precision and recall across language boundaries without significant performance loss. These breakthroughs strongly indicate that the underlying architectural patterns constituting a "smell" share a fundamental geometric or metric similarity across diverse object-oriented languages, allowing properly tuned statistical models to finally transcend the historical Java bias.The Inter-Rater Reliability Bound on Evaluative PrecisionThe most profound, intractable methodological challenge in evaluating automated code smell detectors is not algorithmic or mathematical, but fundamentally human. As early theorists Beck and Fowler originally asserted, bad code smells are "not precise criteria for flaws in program code," but are highly subjective conditions that are "better to be judged based on informed human intuition". This inherent architectural subjectivity implies that even highly experienced, senior developers operating in the same domain will frequently disagree on whether a specific, isolated code fragment constitutes a detrimental smell, and if so, at what severity level it operates.This pervasive disagreement is mathematically formalized in research evaluations using Inter-Rater Reliability (IRR) statistics. The most prominent statistical measures deployed to quantify this agreement on categorical data are Cohen's Kappa ($\kappa$) and Gwet’s AC1 coefficient. While standard percent agreement can be misleading, Cohen's Kappa is rigorous because it calculates the degree of agreement between multiple independent raters while strictly factoring in the statistical probability that they agreed purely by random chance. Alternatively, when evaluating spans of concepts where annotators might partially agree or disagree, researchers occasionally calculate the F1 score at the entity level, effectively treating one human annotator as the ground-truth standard and the other as the predictive reference.Quantifying Human Agreement CeilingsThe values of Cohen's Kappa strictly fall between $0$ and $1.0$, where $0$ indicates incredibly poor agreement (no better than random chance) and $1.0$ indicates mathematically perfect agreement. According to established statistical thresholds proposed by Landis and Koch, a $\kappa$ value exceeding 0.81 is categorized as "almost perfect" agreement, while values between 0.61 and 0.80 are considered "substantial" or "good".In highly constrained, tightly defined technical domains, human agreement on code anomalies can be exceptionally high. For example, in an empirical study where independent raters manually annotated explicitly security-related code smells mapped rigidly to the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) framework, the evaluation achieved a flawless Cohen's Kappa score of 1.0, indicating perfect inter-rater reliability. Similarly, an evaluation utilizing the QSMELL tool to strictly identify quantum-specific code smells based on dynamic analysis achieved a $\kappa$ of 0.904, representing near-perfect consensus among domain experts.However, in the context of generalized, high-level architectural design smells—such as God Class, Feature Envy, or Spaghetti Code—human agreement drops precipitously. The creation of the MLCQ dataset visibly highlighted this reality; researchers discovered that professional developers frequently and intensely disagreed on severity classifications, particularly at the macro class-level, necessitating an extensive, labor-intensive cross-checking phase of 2,175 samples to resolve deep discrepancies. In the foundational Fontana dataset, the stark fact that manual human evaluators categorically rejected 1,160 out of 1,986 tool-identified candidate instances highlights a massive, persistent gulf between algorithmic heuristic rules and the nuanced reality of human engineering intuition.The Subjectivity Ceiling on Algorithmic EvaluationThe implications of Inter-Rater Reliability metrics on evaluative methodology and benchmark validity are profound. If a ground-truth benchmark dataset represents the negotiated consensus of multiple human annotators, the measured inter-rater agreement coefficient effectively acts as a strict, theoretical upper bound on the precision and recall achievable by any valid automated tool.Consider a scenario where human software architects—who possess deep, holistic contextual awareness of business logic, systemic constraints, and longitudinal evolutionary history—can only achieve a Cohen's Kappa of 0.75 or 0.80 when attempting to uniformly identify a Feature Envy smell. If a newly proposed automated machine learning tool or LLM claims to achieve 98% or 100% precision and recall on that exact same dataset, the tool is almost certainly scientifically invalid. It is not successfully mathematically modeling the abstract, universal concept of a code smell; rather, it is catastrophically overfitting to the dataset, merely memorizing the highly specific, subjective biases and localized heuristic preferences of the handful of human annotators who originally labeled the test set.Therefore, when rigorously evaluating state-of-the-art tools against prominent oracles like Landfill, Fontana, or MLCQ, raw precision and recall percentages must always be analyzed critically through the mathematical lens of human agreement. The ultimate objective of an automated code smell detector is not to achieve an illusory 100% precision, as that implies a level of mathematical rigidity that directly contradicts the fluid, subjective nature of software design. Instead, the ultimate goal of an automated detector is to tightly approximate the performance of a highly skilled, context-aware human peer, achieving an agreement coefficient with the ground-truth oracle that closely matches, but does not unnaturally exceed, the inter-rater reliability threshold established by the original human evaluators.Inter-Rater MetricDomain EvaluatedAchieved Score (κ)Implication on Automated EvaluationCohen's KappaGeneral Object-Oriented SmellsOften < 0.80 (Substantial/Moderate)Automated models claiming >95% precision on these tasks are likely overfitting to annotator bias.Cohen's KappaSecurity-mapped Smells (CWE)1.0 (Perfect Agreement)Algorithms can reasonably target near 100% precision due to strict, objective boundary conditions.Cohen's KappaQuantum-specific Smells (QSMELL)0.904 (Almost Perfect)High ceiling for dynamic analysis tools; structural patterns are less ambiguous than Java architecture.Entity-Level F1Subjective Severity ClassificationHighly VariableRequires cross-checking (e.g., MLCQ) to establish a reliable baseline before algorithmic training.Synthesis and Future Methodological OutlookThe continuous evolution of automated code smell detection methodologies is inextricably linked to the rigorous maturation of its benchmark datasets and evaluative oracles. The historical paradigm shift away from purely heuristic static analysis tools—such as basic, threshold-dependent configurations of Checkstyle or PMD—toward complex evolutionary algorithms like HIST and modern machine learning stacking ensembles was fundamentally catalyzed by the development of highly robust ground-truth oracles.Datasets like Palomba's Landfill provided the necessary, high-confidence manual validation that exposed the limitations of traditional heuristics. Arcelli Fontana's dataset subsequently scaled these concepts, enabling the widespread application of multi-label classification algorithms like Random Forests over large feature sets. Finally, the MLCQ dataset introduced a crucial, industry-relevant perspective, decoupling detection from rigid metrics and forcing modern models, including advanced Large Language Models, to grapple with the raw reality of contemporary codebases. Concurrently, datasets like ManySStuBs4J and Defects4J, while primarily designed for automated program repair, continue to illuminate the complex, often tangled relationship between structural code smells and functional bug propagation.As the software engineering field rapidly advances, two primary vectors of research will dominate future evaluation methodologies. First, the necessary breakdown of the entrenched Java monopoly through the development of cross-language benchmarks and instance-based transfer learning models will ensure that architectural quality analysis becomes a universally applicable science, regardless of the underlying language syntax. Second, the widespread recognition of the inter-rater reliability bound will force the research community to fundamentally rethink its performance metrics. Future evaluations will no longer merely chase theoretical 100% precision ceilings; they will embrace the inherent, unavoidable subjectivity of code smells, optimizing automated tools to align seamlessly with the contextual, informed intuition of professional developers rather than fighting against it.